    "science.section1.title": "From Glucose to Fat Metabolism",
    "science.section1.p1": "In a typical Western diet, our cells primarily run on glucose. After a carbohydrate-rich meal, blood glucose rises, prompting the pancreas to release insulin. Insulin helps cells absorb glucose and store excess energy as glycogen and fat, while suppressing fat breakdown in adipose tissue.",
    "science.section1.p2": "The ketogenic diet fundamentally shifts this paradigm. By restricting carbohydrate intake to < 50 grams per day (typically 5–10% of total energy) and increasing fat intake to about 70–80% of calories, you lower insulin and force the body to seek an alternative fuel. Over several days, this drives the liver into ketogenesis, producing ketone bodies and initiating nutritional ketosis.",
    "science.card.triggers": "The Metabolic Shift Triggers",
    "science.card.triggers.desc": "Once carbohydrates are restricted and insulin falls, a cascade of metabolic events begins:",
    "science.card.insulin": "Lower Insulin",
    "science.card.insulin.desc1": "Blood glucose and insulin levels drop significantly.",
    "science.card.insulin.desc2": "Low insulin removes the \"brake\" on fat breakdown.",
    "science.card.insulin.desc3": "Cells become more sensitive to insulin over time, improving metabolic health.",
    "science.card.fat": "Fat Breakdown (Lipolysis)",
    "science.card.fat.desc1": "In adipose tissue, hormone-sensitive lipase (HSL) is activated.",
    "science.card.fat.desc2": "HSL breaks down stored triglycerides into free fatty acids (FFA) and glycerol.",
    "science.card.fat.desc3": "FFA travel through the bloodstream to the liver and other tissues as a major fuel source.",
    "science.card.ketone": "Ketone Production (Ketogenesis)",
    "science.card.ketone.desc1": "Inside the mitochondria of liver cells, free fatty acids undergo β-oxidation, generating acetyl-CoA.",
    "science.card.ketone.desc2": "Excess acetyl-CoA is routed into ketogenesis, producing ketone bodies: β-hydroxybutyrate (BHB), Acetoacetate (AcAc), and Acetone.",
    "science.card.ketone.desc3": "These ketones are then released into the bloodstream and become a central fuel for the brain, heart, and muscles.",
    "science.card.note": "Nutritional ketosis (BHB ~0.5–3.0 mmol/L) is not the same as diabetic ketoacidosis. In nutritional ketosis, pH remains normal, insulin is low but present, and the process is tightly regulated.",
    "science.section2.title": "Ketones as a Superior Fuel Source",
    "science.section2.p1": "Ketone bodies are water-soluble, which means they travel easily through the bloodstream and across cell membranes. Cells in muscle, heart, and brain express transporters (MCTs) that rapidly take up ketones. Inside the cell, ketones are converted back to acetyl-CoA and enter the Krebs cycle (TCA cycle) to produce ATP – the universal energy currency of the cell.",
    "science.section2.subtitle": "Efficient Brain Fuel & Metabolic Flexibility",
    "science.section2.p2": "A key advantage of ketosis is that the brain can obtain a significant share of its energy from ketones, reducing its reliance on glucose. This:",
    "science.section2.list1": "Smooths out blood sugar fluctuations",
    "science.section2.list2": "Can reduce \"energy crashes\" associated with high-carb eating",
    "science.section2.list3": "Helps explain why many people in ketosis report clearer thinking and more stable focus",
    "science.section2.flexibility": "This ability to switch between fuels — glucose when available, ketones when carbs are low — is called metabolic flexibility, and it’s a hallmark of a healthier metabolism.",
    "science.transport.title": "Visualizing Ketone Transport",
    "science.transport.1": "Generated in the liver from fatty acids",
    "science.transport.2": "Released into the bloodstream",
    "science.transport.3": "Rapidly transported via specific carriers to energy-hungry organs",
    "science.transport.4": "Converted to ATP inside mitochondria with impressive efficiency",
    "science.transport.note": "Unlike long-chain fatty acids, ketone bodies don’t require complex packaging in lipoproteins; they move freely in blood, making them a fast, clean, and accessible energy source.",
    "science.infographic.title": "Why Keto Works for Weight Loss (Especially in Obesity)",
    "science.infographic.desc": "This infographic breaks down the scientific mechanisms by which ketogenic diets contribute to weight loss and metabolic improvements. It explains four key pathways: appetite suppression through hunger hormone regulation, increased energy expenditure, insulin reduction and fat mobilization, and the magnitude of weight loss outcomes. Based on meta-analyses and randomized controlled trials (2024-2025), ketogenic diets produce superior weight loss in obesity through multiple complementary mechanisms, with best results achieved when combined with adequate protein intake and resistance training.",
    "science.section3.title": "More Than Just Fuel: Signaling Molecules",
    "science.section3.p1": "Modern research shows that ketones are not just passive energy carriers. They are bioactive signaling molecules that influence inflammation, gene expression, oxidative stress defenses, and metabolic pathways involved in aging and chronic disease.",
    "science.card.anti_inflammatory": "Anti-Inflammatory Effects",
    "science.card.anti_inflammatory.subtitle": "BHB and the NLRP3 inflammasome",
    "science.card.anti_inflammatory.desc1": "The NLRP3 inflammasome is an intracellular complex that amplifies inflammation and is implicated in conditions like obesity, type 2 diabetes, and cardiovascular disease.",
    "science.card.anti_inflammatory.desc2": "BHB directly inhibits NLRP3 activation, reducing production of inflammatory cytokines such as IL-1β and IL-18.",
    "science.card.anti_inflammatory.desc3": "This dampening of chronic, low-grade inflammation can support healthier blood vessels, metabolic tissues, and potentially brain function over time.",
    "science.card.anti_inflammatory.desc4": "In other words, ketones don’t just fuel cells — they help calm down inflammatory signaling at the molecular level.",
    "science.card.epigenetic": "Epigenetic Regulation",
    "science.card.epigenetic.subtitle": "BHB as an epigenetic signal",
    "science.card.epigenetic.desc1": "BHB also acts as:",
